==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|acanthus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ἄκανθος|tr=akanthos|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}}, from {{term|ἀκή|tr=akē||thorn|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}} + {{term|ἄνθος|tr=anthos||flower|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}}.<ref name=WI3>Gove, Philip Babcock, ed. ''Webster's Third International Dictionary of the English Language Unabridged.'' Springfield: G. & C. Merriam Co., 1976.</ref><ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, ed. ''The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary.'' 5th. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2003.</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈkæn.θəs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈkæn.θəs/}}
* {{rhymes|ænθəs}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|acanthuses|acanthi}}

# {{context|botany|lang=en}} A member of the genus ''[[Acanthus]]'' of [[herbaceous]] [[prickly]] plants with toothed leaves, (family [[Acanthaceae]], order ''{{taxlink|Scrophulariales|order|noshow=1}}'') found in the south of Europe, Asia Minor, and India.{{defdate|First attested in the mid 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|architecture|lang=en}} An ornament resembling the [[foliage]] or leaves of {{taxlink|Acanthus spinosus|species|noshow=1}} used in the [[capital]]s of the [[Corinthian]] and [[composite]] orders.{{defdate|First attested in the mid 18th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

